[[File:Kusatsu-Shiranesan01s5s4272.jpg|thumb|image]] '''Manza Onsen''' (万座温泉) is a hot spring located in Hoshimata, {{ill|Tsumagoi Village|ja|嬬恋村|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Agatsuma District|ja|吾妻郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|12=draft|12=draft}}, within the {{ill|Joshinetsu Kogen National Park|ja|上信越高原国立公園|12=draft|12=draft}}, at an elevation of 1,800 m. It is one of the highest hot springs in Japan that can be reached year‑round by private automobile, along with {{ill|Daku River Onsen|ja|濁河温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|ja|岐阜県|12=draft|12=draft}}’s {{ill|Gero City|ja|下呂市|12=draft|12=draft}}. Nearby are three explosive crater lakes: Yubatake, Karagama, and Mizukama.
== Water Quality == * Acidic sulfur spring ({{ill|Hydrogen Sulfide Spring|ja|硫化水素泉|12=draft|12=draft}}) : The water is characterized by its milky white or yellowish appearance and contains the highest sulfur content of any hot spring in Japan. It has a discharge of 3,750 L per minute.
== Onsen Town == [[File:Manza ski resort Mt.Asahi 20080219.jpg|thumb|{{ill|Manza Onsen Ski Resort|ja|万座温泉スキー場|12=draft|12=draft}}]] Located on the slopes of {{ill|Kusatsu Shirane|ja|草津白根山|12=draft|12=draft}}, Manza Onsen was once a thriving hot spring resort ({{ill|Yūji|ja|湯治場|12=draft|12=draft}}) from spring through autumn and is now renowned as a ski destination in winter. The high temperature of its sources causes a continuous plume of steam, and the source areas display a hellish appearance with a pervasive sulfur odor. Hot spring sources emerge abundantly along the riverbed<ref name="noguchi">[[ill|Fuyuhito Noguchi|ja|野口冬人]]『湯治の宿』, Yomiuri Travel Publishing</ref>. A notable vent known as "Karabuki" near the outskirts of the central area is a local specialty (though its steam output has diminished since around 2012). The gently sloping mountainside is dotted with inns and hotels, with the {{ill|Manza Onsen Ski Resort|ja|万座温泉スキー場|12=draft|12=draft}} situated at the rear. Because the area is within a national park, facility expansions or renovations are limited, resulting in many aging structures. Some accommodations have closed or been absorbed by others; as of 2019, only 7 inns and hotels continue independent operations for individual guests. There are also lodging options with self-catering facilities for long-term hot spring therapy, though no convenience stores exist in the area apart from small shops attached to the accommodations. Additionally, the Manza Onsen Ski Resort was featured as a filming location for the movie [[Take Me Skiing]]. There are over 10 hot spring sources, including Yubatake, Banna no Yu, Daiku Yu, Tetsuyu, and Hōsei no Yu.
== History == The period of initial development is unclear; however, Yayoi pottery has been excavated in the vicinity. Legend has it that {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|ja|坂上田村麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}} exorcised demons here, and records indicate that samurai visited for hot spring therapy during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. Although it operated as a hot spring resort during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, it did not flourish until after World War II, when the {{ill|Seibu Group|ja|西武グループ|12=draft|12=draft}} undertook resort development and transportation improved.
On February 22, 1983, the old building of Manza Onsen Hotel (Nisshinkan) caught fire, completely burning an area of 1,000 m². Four ski guests sustained minor injuries. According to the reports of the {{ill|Naganohara Police Station|ja|長野原警察署|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Agatsuma Western Regional Fire Department|ja|吾妻広域西部消防署|12=draft|12=draft}}, although 135 guests were staying in the old building, the deep snow enabled most to escape by jumping from the windows, preventing a far worse tragedy<ref name="mainichi">[[ill|Mainichi Shimbun|ja|毎日新聞]] Evening Edition, February 23, 1983</ref>.
In 2004, during the hot spring misrepresentation scandal, a ryokan was reported to have displayed descriptions on its website suggesting hot spring usage despite not drawing any; subsequent corrections were made. As of 2019, the management of the affected facility has changed.
== Access == * Railway ({{ill|JR East|ja|JR東日本|12=draft|12=draft}}) : Approximately 40 minutes by {{ill|Seibu Sightseeing Bus|ja|西武観光バス|12=draft|12=draft}} from {{ill|Manza-Kashizawa-guchi Station|ja|万座・鹿沢口駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Agatsuma Line|ja|吾妻線|12=draft|12=draft}}. : Approximately 90 minutes by Seibu Sightseeing Bus (via Manza-Kashizawa-guchi Station) from {{ill|Karuizawa Station|ja|軽井沢駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Hokuriku Shinkansen|ja|北陸新幹線|12=draft|12=draft}}. * There are three bus stops in the Manza Onsen area: "Manza Onsen" (near the entrance), the central "Manza Prince Hotel" bus stop, and the "Manza Onsen Ue" bus stop. * Automobile: : The only road available year‑round is the paid {{ill|Manza Highway|ja|万座ハイウェー|12=draft|12=draft}}, about 22 km from Mihara in Tsumagoi Village. : From spring to autumn, {{ill|National Route 292|ja|国道292号|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shiga‑Kusatsu Kogen Route) is available (it is closed in winter). Note that due to the eruption alert level for {{ill|Kusatsu Shirane|ja|草津白根山|12=draft|12=draft}}, the section between the (Kusatsu) {{ill|Sesshōgahara|ja|殺生河原|12=draft|12=draft}} parking area and the Manza Sansaji intersection may be closed. As of April 2019, the eruption alert level is 2; although normally it would be closed all day, an exception allows passage during daytime only (bicycles, motorcycles, and convertibles are not permitted; weather conditions such as fog may also cause closures).
