{{出典の明記|date=March 2017}}{{infobox Onsen | 名称 = Manza Onsen | native_name = 万座温泉 | image = Manza Onsen Tsumagoi Gunma01bs4272.jpg | コメント = Manza-yama and Manza Onsen | 所在地 = [[:en:Gunma Prefecture|Gunma Prefecture]] [[:en:Agatsuma District, Gunma|Agatsuma District]] [[:en:Tsumagoi|Tsumagoi Village]] 干俣 | 緯度度 = 36 | 緯度分 = 38 | 緯度秒 = 5.1 | 経度度 = 138 | 経度分 = 30 | 経度秒 = 31.7 | 交通アクセス = ''See the [[#Access|Access]] section.'' | 泉質 = Acidic sulfur spring | 泉温 = Approximately 80°C | 湧出量 = Approximately 5,400,000 [[:en:Litre|L]]/day | pH = | 液性の分類 = | 浸透圧の分類 = | 宿泊施設数 = 9 | 総収容人員数 = | 年間浴客数 = | 統計年度 = | External links = http://www.manzaonsen.gr.jp/ | 特記事項 = }}
[[File:Kusatsu-Shiranesan01s5s4272.jpg|thumb|image]] '''Manza Onsen''' (万座温泉) is a hot spring located in Hoshimata, [[:en:Tsumagoi|Tsumagoi Village]], [[:en:Agatsuma District, Gunma|Agatsuma District]], [[:en:Gunma Prefecture|Gunma Prefecture]], within the [[:en:Jōshin'etsu-kōgen National Park|Joshinetsu Kogen National Park]], at an elevation of 1,800 m. It is one of the highest hot springs in Japan that can be reached year‑round by private automobile, along with {{ill|Daku River Onsen|ja|濁河温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daku River Onsen|qq=}} in [[:en:Gifu Prefecture|Gifu Prefecture]]’s [[:en:Gero, Gifu|Gero City]]. Nearby are three explosive crater lakes: Yubatake, Karagama, and Mizukama.
== Water Quality == * Acidic sulfur spring ({{ill|Hydrogen Sulfide Spring|ja|硫化水素泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hydrogen Sulfide Spring|qq=}}) : The water is characterized by its milky white or yellowish appearance and contains the highest sulfur content of any hot spring in Japan. It has a discharge of 3,750 L per minute.
== Onsen Town == [[File:Manza ski resort Mt.Asahi 20080219.jpg|thumb|{{ill|Manza Onsen Ski Resort|ja|万座温泉スキー場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manza Onsen Ski Resort|qq=}}]] Located on the slopes of [[:en:Mount Kusatsu-Shirane|Kusatsu Shirane]], Manza Onsen was once a thriving hot spring resort ({{ill|Yūji|ja|湯治場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yūji|qq=}}) from spring through autumn and is now renowned as a ski destination in winter. The high temperature of its sources causes a continuous plume of steam, and the source areas display a hellish appearance with a pervasive sulfur odor. Hot spring sources emerge abundantly along the riverbed<ref name="noguchi">[[ill|Fuyuhito Noguchi|ja|野口冬人]]『湯治の宿』, Yomiuri Travel Publishing</ref>. A notable vent known as "Karabuki" near the outskirts of the central area is a local specialty (though its steam output has diminished since around 2012). The gently sloping mountainside is dotted with inns and hotels, with the {{ill|Manza Onsen Ski Resort|ja|万座温泉スキー場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manza Onsen Ski Resort|qq=}} situated at the rear. Because the area is within a national park, facility expansions or renovations are limited, resulting in many aging structures. Some accommodations have closed or been absorbed by others; as of 2019, only 7 inns and hotels continue independent operations for individual guests. There are also lodging options with self-catering facilities for long-term hot spring therapy, though no convenience stores exist in the area apart from small shops attached to the accommodations. Additionally, the Manza Onsen Ski Resort was featured as a filming location for the movie [[Take Me Skiing]]. There are over 10 hot spring sources, including Yubatake, Banna no Yu, Daiku Yu, Tetsuyu, and Hōsei no Yu.
== History == The period of initial development is unclear; however, Yayoi pottery has been excavated in the vicinity. Legend has it that [[:en:Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro]] exorcised demons here, and records indicate that samurai visited for hot spring therapy during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}. Although it operated as a hot spring resort during the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], it did not flourish until after World War II, when the {{ill|Seibu Group|ja|西武グループ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seibu Group|qq=}} undertook resort development and transportation improved.
On February 22, 1983, the old building of Manza Onsen Hotel (Nisshinkan) caught fire, completely burning an area of 1,000 m². Four ski guests sustained minor injuries. According to the reports of the {{ill|Naganohara Police Station|ja|長野原警察署|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Naganohara Police Station|qq=}} and the {{ill|Agatsuma Western Regional Fire Department|ja|吾妻広域西部消防署|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Agatsuma Western Regional Fire Department|qq=}}, although 135 guests were staying in the old building, the deep snow enabled most to escape by jumping from the windows, preventing a far worse tragedy<ref name="mainichi">[[ill|Mainichi Shimbun|ja|毎日新聞]] Evening Edition, February 23, 1983</ref>.
In 2004, during the hot spring misrepresentation scandal, a ryokan was reported to have displayed descriptions on its website suggesting hot spring usage despite not drawing any; subsequent corrections were made. As of 2019, the management of the affected facility has changed.
== Access == * Railway ({{ill|JR East|ja|JR東日本|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR East|qq=}}) : Approximately 40 minutes by {{ill|Seibu Sightseeing Bus|ja|西武観光バス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seibu Sightseeing Bus|qq=}} from [[:en:Manza-Kazawaguchi Station|Manza-Kashizawa-guchi Station]] on the [[:en:Agatsuma Line|Agatsuma Line]]. : Approximately 90 minutes by Seibu Sightseeing Bus (via Manza-Kashizawa-guchi Station) from [[:en:Karuizawa Station|Karuizawa Station]] on the [[:en:Hokuriku Shinkansen|Hokuriku Shinkansen]]. * There are three bus stops in the Manza Onsen area: "Manza Onsen" (near the entrance), the central "Manza Prince Hotel" bus stop, and the "Manza Onsen Ue" bus stop. * Automobile: : The only road available year‑round is the paid {{ill|Manza Highway|ja|万座ハイウェー|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manza Highway|qq=}}, about 22 km from Mihara in Tsumagoi Village. : From spring to autumn, [[:en:Japan National Route 292|National Route 292]] (Shiga‑Kusatsu Kogen Route) is available (it is closed in winter). Note that due to the eruption alert level for [[:en:Mount Kusatsu-Shirane|Kusatsu Shirane]], the section between the (Kusatsu) {{ill|Sesshōgahara|ja|殺生河原|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sesshōgahara|qq=}} parking area and the Manza Sansaji intersection may be closed. As of April 2019, the eruption alert level is 2; although normally it would be closed all day, an exception allows passage during daytime only (bicycles, motorcycles, and convertibles are not permitted; weather conditions such as fog may also cause closures).
