[[File:Kusatsu-Shiranesan01s5s4272.jpg|thumb|image]] '''Manza Onsen''' (万座温泉) is a hot spring located in Hoshimata, {{ill|Tsumagoi|en|Tsumagoi|qid=Q1203321|lt=Tsumagoi Village|1=Tsumagoi}}, {{ill|Agatsuma District, Gunma|en|Agatsuma District, Gunma|qid=Q642394|lt=Agatsuma District|1=Agatsuma District, Gunma}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|en|Gunma Prefecture|qid=Q129499|lt=Gunma Prefecture|1=Gunma Prefecture}}, within the {{ill|Jōshin'etsu-kōgen National Park|en|Jōshin'etsu-kōgen National Park|qid=Q1155306|lt=Joshinetsu Kogen National Park|1=Jōshin'etsu-kōgen National Park}}, at an elevation of 1,800 m. It is one of the highest hot springs in Japan that can be reached year-round by private automobile, along with {{ill|Daku River Onsen|ja|濁河温泉|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daku River Onsen|1=Nigorigo Onsen|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11566108}} in {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|en|Gifu Prefecture|qid=Q131277|lt=Gifu Prefecture|1=Gifu Prefecture}}’s {{ill|Gero, Gifu|en|Gero, Gifu|qid=Q819639|lt=Gero City|1=Gero, Gifu}}. Nearby are three explosive crater lakes: Yubatake, Karagama, and Mizukama.
== Water Quality == * Acidic sulfur spring ({{ill|Hydrogen Sulfide Spring|ja|硫化水素泉|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hydrogen Sulfide Spring|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 硫黄泉|1=Sulfur spring|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11587679}}) : The water is characterized by its milky white or yellowish appearance and contains the highest sulfur content of any hot spring in Japan. It has a discharge of 3,750 L per minute.
