kiing]]. There are over 10 hot spring sources, including Yubatake, Banna no Yu, Daiku Yu, Tetsuyu, and Hōsei no Yu.
== History == The period of initial development is unclear; however, Yayoi pottery has been excavated in the vicinity. Legend has it that {{ill|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|en|Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|qid=Q941979|lt=Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|1=Sakanoue no Tamuramaro}} exorcised demons here, and records indicate that samurai visited for hot spring therapy during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|1=Sengoku Period (Japan)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q117415390}}. Although it operated as a hot spring resort during the {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|qid=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}, it did not flourish until after World War II, when the {{ill|Seibu Group|ja|西武グループ|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seibu Group|1=Seibu Group|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11628875}} undertook resort development and transportation improved.
